               Apply for Social Security Retirement Benefits Online!

   News Articles from 9/01

   ""

   Swindlers, Hucksters and Snake Oil Salesmen
   On September 10 the Senate Special Committee on Aging held a hearing on
   phony anti-aging products. One recurrent theme is that the public
   should have better access to information about dietary supplements.
   There is a handy checklist for senior consumers of dietary supplements.
   Also visit the National Center for Complementary and Alternative
   Medicine (NCCAM) at the National Institutes of Health.

   ""
   Dietary Supplement T3 Recalled
   Global Enterprises is recalling T3, a dietary supplement containing
   tiratricol, a potent thyroid hormone that may cause serious health
   consequences, including heart attacks and strokes.

   ""
   New Breast Cancer Treatment Combines Two Drugs
   FDA has approved a combination of the cancer drugs Xeloda
   (capecitabine) and Taxotere (docetaxel) for treating patients with
   metastatic breast cancer that has progressed after treatment with an
   anthracycline-containing therapy.

   ""
   FDA Weighs In On The Importation Of Drugs
   Thinking of buying drugs overseas? See what the Food and Drug
   Administration has to say about importing drugs for personal use. Heres
   the congressional testimony of William K. Hubbard, Senior Associate
   Commissioner for Policy, Planning and Legislation, FDA.

   ""
   National Family Caregiver Support Program (NFCSP)
   The Older Americans Act Amendments of 2000 established the NFCSP.  A
   web site was established to assist the aging network in developing
   caregiver support programs. A recent addition includes reports from a
   recent conference that are primarily addressed to caregiver
   professionals.

   ""
   Medicare/Medicaid Consumer Protection Tips
   Health care error, fraud, and abuse affect everyone. They contribute to
   the rising costs of health care and, in some instances, diminish the
   quality of care that is provided. This Administration on Aging web site
   provides valuable tips to protect these national services. And learn
   more about the Senior Medicare Patrol.

"" More On Stem Cell Research:


   [blubul3a.gif] HHS Secretary Tommy G. Thompsons September 5th testimony
   before the Senate Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee
   regarding embryonic stem cell research.
   [blubul3a.gif] The National Institutes of Health announced the signing
   of a Memorandum of Understanding with the WiCell Research Institute,
   Inc., for research use of WiCell's existing five human embryonic stem
   cell lines that meet the President's criteria for federal research
   funding.
   [blubul3a.gif] The Food and Drug Administration response to questions
   about stem cell research.

   "" Stem Cell Research Announcement From NIH
   The National Institutes of Health released a statement regarding stem
   cell research. The statement includes a list of the companies,
   laboratories, and organizations that hold human embryonic stem cells.

   ""
   Clinical Trials Site Debuts
   Clinical trials have come under scrutiny in the news. The FDA has a
   timely new site that explains Good Clinical Practice (GCP) in
   FDA-regulated clinical trials. GCP standards ensure that trial results
   are credible and that the rights of trial subjects are protected.

   "" Research Tools On Aging
   Need to research on aging issues? Visit the SeniorsCitizens Gerontology
   Geriatric Aging Research Center. This site has web links on statistics,
   journals, books, and Internet sites.

   ""
   Protein After Exercise Boosts Muscle in Older Men
   Consuming a high-protein supplement shortly after strength training may
   help healthy older men ward off the muscle loss that comes with age.

   "" Relief From Tinnitus
   Do you hear a ringing, roaring, clicking, or hissing sound in your
   ears? Do you hear this sound often or all the time? Does the sound
   bother you a lot? You may have tinnitus, and this Medline web site
   could help you.

   "" HHS Launches New Web Site Dedicated To Global Health Issues
   HHS Secretary Tommy G. Thompson announced the launch of a new Web site
   that addresses the inextricable link between domestic and international
   health issues.




